          "Definitions:\n• Morgenthau: \"The meaning of national interest is survival — the protection of physical, political, and cultural identity.\"\n• Charles Lerche & Abdul Said: \"National Interest is the general, long-term and continuing purpose which the state, the nation, and the government all see themselves as serving.\"\n• Joseph Frankel: \"National interest is a key concept in foreign policy.\"\n\nClassification (Thomas Robinson):\n1. PRIMARY/VITAL INTERESTS:\n• Preservation of sovereignty and territorial integrity\n• Protection of political system and national identity\n• Survival of the state — non-negotiable\n\n2. SECONDARY INTERESTS:\n• Protection of citizens abroad\n• Diplomatic immunities\n• Trade agreements and economic cooperation\n\n3. PERMANENT INTERESTS:\n• Long-term goals that persist over time\n• E.g., India's interest in regional stability\n\n4. VARIABLE INTERESTS:\n• Change with circumstances\n• E.g., alliances during wartime\n\n5. GENERAL INTERESTS:\n• Apply to many nations\n• E.g., freedom of navigation, free trade\n\n6. SPECIFIC INTERESTS:\n• Particular to one nation\n• E.g., India's interest in Kashmir",
